value.def: A parade is a procession of people or vehicles moving through a public place in order to celebrate an important day or event.

example.ex: A military parade marched slowly and solemnly down Pennsylvania Avenue.
example.tran: 阅兵队列沿宾夕法尼亚大道缓慢而庄严地行进。

value.tran: （庆祝重大日子或事件的）游行行列

value.def: When people parade somewhere, they walk together in a formal group or a line, usually with other people watching them.

example.ex: More than four thousand soldiers, sailors and airmen paraded down the Champs Elysee...
example.tran: 逾4,000名陆、海、空三军将士在香榭丽舍大街游行。

example.ex: Everybody was beginning to parade back to the village.
example.tran: 大家开始成群结队地返回村庄。

value.def: Parade is a formal occasion when soldiers stand in lines to be seen by an officer or important person, or march in a group.

example.ex: He had them on parade at six o'clock in the morning...
example.tran: 他让他们早晨6点列队接受检阅。

example.ex: Morning parade was in progress on the parade ground.
example.tran: 阅兵场正在进行早间检阅。

value.def: If flags or statues are paraded, they are carried in a procession.

example.ex: Banners were paraded from church to church on feast days.
example.tran: 宗教节日期间，人们打着横幅在教堂间游行。

value.def: If prisoners are paraded through the streets of a town or on television, they are shown to the public, usually in order to make the people who are holding them seem more powerful or important.

example.ex: Five leading fighter pilots have been captured and paraded before the media.
example.tran: 有5名一流的战斗机飞行员被俘，并被在媒体上曝光。

value.tran: 将（囚犯）游街；将（囚犯）示众

value.def: If you say that someone parades a person, you mean that they show that person to others only in order to gain some advantage for themselves.

example.ex: Children are paraded on television alongside the party leaders to win votes.
example.tran: 为了拉选票，孩子们被拉去和政党领袖们一起出现在电视上。

value.def: If people parade something, they show it in public so that it can be admired.

example.ex: Valentino is keen to see celebrities parading his clothes at big occasions.
example.tran: 瓦伦蒂诺喜欢看名人在重大场合展示他设计的服装。

value.def: If someone parades, they walk about somewhere in order to be seen and admired.

example.ex: I love to put on a bathing suit and parade on the beach...
example.tran: 我喜欢穿着泳衣在海滩上招摇而行。

value.def: If someone parades a real or pretended feeling or quality, they draw attention to themselves by displaying it.

example.ex: They parade their virtuous beliefs and hide their vices...
example.tran: 他们大秀美德并掩盖自己的罪恶。

example.ex: Women were not supposed to parade their ambition nakedly.
example.tran: 女性被认为不应该赤裸裸地展示其雄心。

value.def: If you say that something parades as or is paraded as a good or important thing, you mean that some people say that it is good or important but you think it probably is not.

example.ex: The Chancellor will be able to parade his cut in interest rates as a small victory...
example.tran: 财政大臣就能把他的减息举措当作一场小胜来夸耀了。

example.ex: She might have been paraded as a woman who was working hard to change her ways.
example.tran: 她可能已经被吹嘘成一个靠努力工作改变命运的女人了。

example.ex: ...all the fashions that parade as modern movements in art.
example.tran: 标榜为现代艺术运动的所有流行时尚

value.def: If you talk about a parade of people or things, you mean that there is a series of them that seems never to end.

example.ex: When I ask Nick about his childhood, he remembers a parade of babysitters.
example.tran: 我问到尼克的童年生活时，他记起了一个又一个保姆。

value.tran: （多得似乎没有尽头的）一系列

value.def: A parade is a short row of shops, usually set back from the main street.
value.tran: （常指远离大街的）一小排店铺

value.def: Parade is used as part of the name of a street.

example.tran: 南海克拉伦斯商业街皇后酒店
